default (WRT 030)
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;
defaultBritish Airways welcomes the opportunity to contribute to the Transport Select Committee’s inquiry into 
defaultWinter Resilience in Transport.
default&#xa0;
defaultBritish Airways is one of the world’s leading global premium airlines and the UK’s largest international scheduled airline, carrying approximately 37 million passengers worldwide annually, on around 830 daily flights.  The 
defaultairline employs around 40,000 people, the vast majority of these at its sites throughout the UK, and has an annual turnover of over £9 billion.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe airline’s two main operating bases are London’s Heathrow and Gatwick airports, with a smaller base at Londo
defaultn City airport serving New York, European and domestic destinations.  From these three, British Airways flies over 280 aircraft to 173 destinations in more than 80 countries. In addition to passengers, the airline also transports cargo – more than 785,000 
defaulttonnes of cargo are carried around the globe each year. 
default&#xa0;
defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;
default1.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultBritish Airways’ main operating base, Heathrow, is one of the world’s busiest international airports. Unlike other major competitor hubs in Europe, Heathrow has been operating for many year
defaults at full capacity throughout most of the day. It is further constrained by rigorous limits on night movements and restrictions on how the capacity of its two runways is maximised. Therefore it is vital that the impact of this operating environment is full
defaulty understood when considering the response of airlines and airport operators to winter weather disruption. 
default&#xa0;
default1.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhile British Airways will continue to do everything in its power to minimise both the incidence and the impact of weather disruption, it is important to note that responsibility must lie with the airport operators and their service partners for ensuring t
defaulthat the airport, including runways, taxiways, aprons, service roads and public access points to and from the airport, are resilient to adverse weather conditions. Heathrow Airport Limited and Gatwick Airport Limited, together with other airport operators, 
defaultmust continue to prioritise snow preparedness and provide timely, reliable and proactive responses both prior to, and during adverse weather events. 
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe impact of winter weather disruption on airport and airline operations is different for each event and
default is highly dependent on the nature and duration of the adverse weather conditions. Despite robust contingency planning, airlines would never be able to guarantee operating a full schedule during times of significant weather disruption. This is particularly
default the case at capacity constrained airports on the British Airways network, especially Heathrow. 
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt should be noted that Heathrow is not the only airport affected by winter weather disruption. In fact most UK airports, including Gatwick and London City, a
defaultnd many in Western Europe, including Paris, Frankfurt and Amsterdam, also suffer disruption during adverse winter weather conditions. However disruption at Heathrow is usually a result of a complex set of factors, key among which is the challenge presented
default by attempting to recover following any operational disruption at an airport which is operating at full capacity. At peak periods of travel demand, the capability for airlines to re-book and reaccommodate disrupted customers is more challenging and does ha
defaultve a more detrimental customer impact for a longer duration.
default&#xa0;
default1.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultBritish Airways has a significant operating presence at three of the key London Airports – Heathrow, Gatwick and London City – and any disruption will therefore have a disproportionate impact on
default the airline’s operations. This is especially the case at Heathrow where British Airways is the hub carrier.
default&#xa0;
default1.6
default&#xa0; 
defaultSince 2010 British Airways has committed significant resources to planning and preparing for adverse winter weather conditions and the airline has
default held a company-wide review of its disruption planning process. In 2013 British Airways is investing over £18 million in improving its customers’ experience during times of disruption, and ensuring that British Airways staff can be mobilised effectively to
default deal with such disruption. The investment consists of developing new tools and technologies, as well as improving our training and processes.
default&#xa0;
default1.7
default&#xa0; 
defaultBritish Airways is committed to improving the experience for its customers during disruption and their welfare i
defaults extremely important to us. The airline has put in place improved resilience and contingency measures to deal with severe weather conditions through its Disruption Management Programme. British Airways is also working closely with the key airport operator
defaults and service par
defaulttners to ensure that they 
defaultare
default also
default suitably prepared to provide welfare support for our customers during disruption. 
