defaultAll of the UK and Ireland airports are prepared for the coming winter. Our de-icing providers have assured us that they have equipm
defaultent, manpower and de-icing fluid ready and in place at all stations to ensure that an effective and rigorous de-icing process is delivered on British Airways’ behalf. In support of the de-icing programme, our airport teams work with the various airport ope
defaultrators to ensure they have a robust airside and landside snow plan, ensuring our customers, colleagues and aircraft can move and operate safely in winter conditions.
default&#xa0;
default4.11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhere cancellations are unavoidable, our airport teams have plans in place to handle disr
defaultuption up to and including full programme cancellations. The teams prepare weekly updates of hotel accommodation, coach and baggage delivery providers in order to understand potential pinch points or threats to our operation. This is shared between the tea
defaultms and held in readiness should disruption occur. Finally, we are communicating with our 
defaultoffline diversion stations (airports which are not normally served by British Airways) regarding their readiness and ability to handle diversions this winter, includin
defaultg airport infrastructure, local hotel and coach providers, and any other key details that we can use to prepare for disruption.
default&#xa0;
default4.12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAll of the above are constantly being reviewed and revised where necessary. The team share learning and collaborate with 
defaultservice providers and colleagues alike to ensure we deliver the best we can for the customer in challenging circumstances.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default5default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat more should be done to ensure a coordinated response?default&#xa0;default6.1 
defaultHeathrow Demand and Capacity Balancing Group (HADACAB)defaultA key 
defaultrecommendation of the Begg Inquiry in 2011, following the snow disruption of December 2010, was for Heathrow Airport to proactively declare a reduced capacity based on the forecast weather to enable the airlines to proactively amend their schedule in order
default to give customers advanced notification of revised schedules. To date this has taken the form of the HADACAB – Heathrow Demand and Capacity Balancing Group – process. HADACAB is backed by a local rule at Heathrow which mandates airlines to follow its inst
defaultructions. Its main drawback though has been identified by British Airways, Heathrow Airport Ltd and NATS as having no power to mandate schedule reductions or changes in advance of an expected adverse event. It only comes into effect once the disruption has
default commenced. Up to now HADACAB has been reluctant to invoke proactive capacity reduction, and on occasions where the decision has been made, compliance by the airlines has been poor and inconsistent. It is worth noting that airports such as Paris Charles De
default Gaulle, under the auspices of the Directorate General of Civil Aviation, act consistently and ensure compliance.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn order to improve the effectiveness of HADACAB, thereby giving passengers more accurate information of the flying programme, airlines need 
defaultconfidence that Heathrow Airport Ltd will invoke HADACAB and take the necessary proactive capacity decisions and that all carriers will abide by the rules, that the reductions necessary are proportionate, that the Met Office forecasts they are based upon a
defaultre accurate and reliable, and finally, that airlines will not be liable for future claims under EU261 rules for cancellations made under a HADACAB determination. The CAA has indicated on the last point that they are sympathetic but it would be very useful 
defaultfor the Department for Transport to take a proactive role in confirming this. 
default&#xa0;
default6.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultThere is an urgent need for the UK government and the CAA to work with relevant European institutions to provide airlines with reassurance that, where cancellations or delays a
defaultre caused by collective decisions in a properly governed decision-making body such as HADACAB, airlines which comply with requests to implement capacity reductions in the interest of minimising disruption to passengers overall, will not be liable to provid
defaulte compensation to those passengers who are disrupted under EU261. Clarity on this issue will be vital if the airline community is to commit to full participation in implementing the decisions of HADACAB.
